  "4": {
    "Edgar V. McKnight": "The roll call of those who live \u201cby faith\u201d begins with Abel `[char_Abel_Gen_4]`. The\nsource material for the author includes the Old Testament and\nJewish and Christian traditions, and the schema of faith as set forth\nin\nv. 4). The writer depended on\n[v_Gen_4_3] Genesis 4:3-5a for this statement. [Genesis 4:2b-10: Genesis Account of\nAbel `[char_Abel_Gen_4]`] The later Jewish tradition expanded the treatment of Abel `[char_Abel_Gen_4]`.\nTwo questions were of special interest: (1) why God had regard for\nAbel `[char_Abel_Gen_4]`\u2019s offering but rejected Cain `[char_Cain_Gen_4]`\u2019s offering and (2) how the two\nbrothers knew that God accepted Abel `[char_Abel_Gen_4]`\u2019s sacrifice rather than Cain `[char_Cain_Gen_4]`\u2019s.\nThe author of Hebrews, however, had little interest in the elabora-\ntion of the biblical narrative. The fact that Abel `[char_Abel_Gen_4]` offered his sacrifice\n\u201cby faith\u201d is sufficient.\nv. 4). Then",
    "John Trapp": "A more excellent sacrifice ] Good actions and good aims make a man good in the sight of God. Cain may offer as well as Abel `[char_Abel_Gen_4]`. Doeg may set his foot as far within the sanctuary as David `[char_David_Rut_4]`, the Pharisee as the publican, but with different success. God testifying of his gifts ] By fire from heaven, or some other visible expression of his gracious acceptation, whereby Abel `[char_Abel_Gen_4]`\u2019s faith was confirmed touching life and salvation in Christ. Paulus Phagius tells us out of the Rabbins, that a face of a lion was seen in the heavenly fire inflaming the sacrifice. (Armor. in Chal. Paraphr.) Which (if it be true) did probably shadow out the \"Lion of the tribe of Judah,\" of whom all the sacrifices were types. Being dead yet speaketh ] \u03bb\u03b1\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9, or, is yet spoken of, being register ed for the first martyr in the Old Testament, as Stephen was in the New, and as Mr Rogers was here in the Marian persecution.\nVer.\n4. God therefore honoureth faith, according to #1Sa 2:30, and gives it his testimonial, as here in this truly named golden legend.\nVer.\n4. A more excellent sacrifice] Good actions and good aims make a man good in the sight of God. Cain may offer as well as Abel `[char_Abel_Gen_4]`. Doeg may set his foot as far within the sanctuary as David `[char_David_Rut_4]`, the Pharisee as the publican, but with different success. God testifying of his gifts] By fire from heaven, or some other visible expression of his gracious acceptation, whereby Abel `[char_Abel_Gen_4]`\u2019s faith was confirmed touching life and salvation in Christ. Paulus Phagius tells us out of the Rabbins, that a face of a lion was seen in the heavenly fire inflaming the sacrifice. (Armor. in Chal. Paraphr.) Which (if it be true) did probably shadow out the \"Lion of the tribe of Judah,\" of whom all the sacrifices were types. Being dead yet speaketh] \u03bb\u03b1\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9, or, is yet spoken of, being registered for the first martyr in the Old Testament, as Stephen was in the New, and as Mr Rogers was here in the Marian persecution.\nVer."
  },
